<subSubSection id="C6C57ACAFFDCFFE8FF28FBA943891DF5" pageId="2" pageNumber="487" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8E602941FFDCFFE8FF28FBA943891DF5" blockId="2.[159,781,662,1163]" pageId="2" pageNumber="487">
<emphasis id="BCABF553FFDCFFE8FF28FBA9404F1D32" bold="true" box="[159,286,1077,1100]" pageId="2" pageNumber="487">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name 
<taxonomicName id="49DF52C2FFDCFFE8FE2FFBA9408D1D32" authorityName="BROWER" authorityYear="2010" box="[408,476,1077,1100]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Astraptes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="487" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="favilla">
<emphasis id="BCABF553FFDCFFE8FE2FFBA9408D1D32" box="[408,476,1077,1100]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="487">favilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a feminine noun in apposition, means ‘smouldering embers’. The species is named in recognition of the skipper taxonomist John M. Burns.
</paragraph>
